    <title>Combined summary - Re: Safer sighashes and more granular SIGHASH_NOINPUT</title>
    <updated>2025-11-12T03:51:15.624963+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://gnusha.org/pi/bitcoindev/20181128140412.GC22873@mcelrath.org/T/#mff4cd99b6609c726ef37157467b1dd9b5bd54cc7" rel="alternate"/>
    <published>2018-11-19 22:37:00+00:00</published>
    <summary>The ongoing discussions and proposals around Bitcoin's script enhancements, specifically concerning the SIGHASH_NOINPUT flag and its potential combination with OP_MASK and OP_CODESEPARATOR, illustrate the community's efforts to balance security, functionality, and complexity in the protocol. The introduction of SIGHASH_NOINPUT is debated due to its implications on key reuse and transaction replayability, highlighting a significant shift from Bitcoin's current security assumptions. While some argue that SIGHASH_NOINPUT's flexibility could enable new use cases like eltoo for Lightning Network, concerns about its safety and complexity lead to suggestions like appending &quot;_UNSAFE&quot; to its name or combining it with mechanisms like script masking to limit its scope.
The concept of script masking, as introduced, aims to mitigate some of the risks associated with SIGHASH_NOINPUT by allowing signatures to commit to a masked version of the script, thus providing a way to specify which parts of a script can change post-signature without affecting signature validity. This could potentially safeguard against certain replay attacks while still enabling the dynamic rebinding of signatures to inputsâ€”a critical feature for protocols like eltoo.
However, the utility and implementation complexity of script masking and OP_CODESEPARATOR under these new sighash flags are subjects of debate. The necessity of committing to the masked script or the position of the last executed OP_CODESEPARATOR to ensure the security and functionality of NOINPUT transactions is weighed against the simplicity and safety of the core protocol. Proposals suggest simplifying or altering how scripts and signatures interact, such as always removing OP_MASKs during signing or questioning the future relevance of OP_CODESEPARATOR in a taproot and MAST environment where alternative scripting mechanisms might render it obsolete.
Furthermore, there's discussion around the historical context and specific use cases where CODESEPARATOR has been utilized, including its role in enabling scriptless scripts or making scripts more compact. Yet, with the advent of Schnorr signatures and taproot, which provide more efficient and privacy-enhancing ways to structure Bitcoin transactions, the community is evaluating whether these older opcodes and sighash types will remain useful or if they should be adapted or deprecated in favor of newer, safer constructs that better align with Bitcoin's evolving script capabilities.
In summary, these discussions reflect the community's careful consideration of trade-offs between enhancing Bitcoin's scripting language to support advanced features like the Lightning Network's eltoo mechanism and maintaining the security, simplicity, and robustness of the protocol. As these proposals evolve, they highlight the ongoing efforts to innovate within Bitcoin's consensus rules while prioritizing user safety and network integrity.</summary>
